MaxMs=2988.4 eventLoopUtilization=0.4 cpuCoreRatio=0.488 active=1 waiting=0 queued=1\",\"_meta\":{\"runtime\":\"node\",\"runtimeVersion\":\"22.22.2\",\"hostname\":\"unknown\",\"name\":\"{\\\"subsystem\\\":\\\"diagnostic\\\"}\",\"parentNames\":[\"openclaw\"],\"date\":\"2026-05-03T11:05:36.943Z\",\"logLevelId\":4,\"logLevelName\":\"WARN\",\"path\":{\"fullFilePath\":\"file:///home/halei/.npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/subsystem-Bhq-McUP.js:150:14\",\"fileName\":\"subsystem-Bhq-McUP.js\",\"fileNameWithLine\":\"subsystem-Bhq-McUP.js:150\",\"fileColumn\":\"14\",\"fileLine\":\"150\",\"filePath\":\".npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/subsystem-Bhq-McUP.js\",\"filePathWithLine\":\".npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/subsystem-Bhq-McUP.js:150\",\"method\":\"logToFile\"}},\"time\":\"2026-05-03T19:05:36.944+08:00\",\"hostname\":\"halei-Surface-Pro-4\",\"message\":\"liveness warning: reasons=event_loop_delay interval=30s eventLoopDelayP99Ms=470 eventLoopDelayMaxMs=2988.4 eventLoopUtilization=0.4 cpuCoreRatio=0.488 active=1 waiting=0 queued=1\"}[... 39304 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["status","exitCode","durationMs","aggregated","cwd"],"status":"completed","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace","exitCode":0},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777806356115}}
{"type":"message","id":"6ab0c9da","parentId":"f3bd45b3","timestamp":"2026-05-03T11:07:05.883Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the logs, I can see the problem. After the config was updated and the gateway restarted, there's this error:\n\n```\ntools.allow allowlist contains unknown entries (taskflow, acp-router, channel-feishu, feishu). These entries won't match any tool unless the plugin is enabled.\n```\n\nAnd then:\n```\nNo callable tools remain after resolving explicit tool allowlist (tools.allow: taskflow, acp-router, channel-feishu, feishu); no registered tools matched.\n```\n\nThis is because `tools.profile` was set to `minimal`, but the tools `taskflow` and `acp-router` aren't registered as tools - they're skills. \n\nSo the issue is that `minimal` profile has its own tool allowlist and we overrode it with just `taskflow` and `acp-router` - but those aren't actual tools, they're skills. The skills like `taskflow` and `acp-router` need to be enabled as skills, not listed as tools.\n\nLooking at the config after our edit:\n```json\n\"tools\": {\n    \"profile\": \"minimal\",\n    \"allow\": [\"taskflow\", \"acp-router\"],\n    \"deny\": [\"*\"]\n}\n```\n\nThe `minimal` profile probably has a default allow list that we're now overriding, but `taskflow` and `acp-router` aren't tool names - they're skill names. So the effective allow list becomes just those two skill names, which don't match any actual tools, resulting in no callable tools.\n\nThe user wanted to use `minimal` profile and only allow `taskflow` and `acp-router`, but it seems like the minimal profile's defaults got replaced entirely instead of being augmented. the effective allowlist becomes just `taskflow` and `acp-router` with `deny: *`. Since neither of these are actual tool names, no tools match and everything gets blocked. I need to figure out what the actual minimal profile defaults are, but regardless, the user likely didn't intend to block all tools—they probably just wanted to use minimal as a base and add taskflow and acp-router to it, or they wanted taskflow and acp-router as exceptions to a minimal restrictionset.\n\nLooking at the log message, the allowlist contains unknown entries because skills aren't tools—`taskflow` and `acp-router` are skill IDs, not tool IDs. So the real problem is that the user added skills to `tools.allow` when they should be in `skills.allow` instead. The configuration change blocked all tools because nothing matched the allowlist, which is why the webchat wasn't responding. But wait—the user is talking to me right now through webchat, so maybe it's working after the restart.\n\nActually, rereading their message: they said \"飞书不行\" which means Feishu isn't working, and now \"通信终于通了\" means communication finally got through. So they're confirming webchat is working now. But they're still asking about Feishu specifically. Let me check what Feishu-related errors appear in the logs, particularly around the time they reported the issue. I saw some gateway-related errors earlier, but I need to focus on the Feishu-specific failures.\n\nThe key issue is clear from the logs though: `tools.allow` has `taskflow` and `acp-router` listed as allowed entries, but the system is warning that these aren't actual tools—they're skills. This means the allowlist configuration is incorrect and nothing is actually being allowed through.\n\nThe problem stems from applying `tools.deny: [\"*\"]` with `tools.allow: [\"taskflow\", \"acp-router\"]` when those aren't valid tool identifiers. To fix this, I either need to specify the actual tool names that should be allowed, or revert to using `tools.profile: \"minimal\"` without the explicit deny rule if that's what was intended.\n\nLooking at the trace logs, I can see the actual tool names being invoked—things like `session-workspace`, `image-tool`, `web-search-tool`, `message-tool`—which are the real identifiers I should be using in the allowlist instead of the skill names. The allowlist configuration with `deny: [\"*\"]` is blocking all tools because the system doesn't recognize \"taskflow\" or \"acp-router\" as valid tool names, only as skill references. Looking at the trace output, the core tools being used are `session-workspace`, `image-tool`, `web-search-tool`, `web-fetch-tool`, `message-tool`, and `nodes-tool`. But I'm realizing `taskflow` and `acp-router` are actually skill files in the workspace, not standalone tools, so they wouldn't appear in this tool allowlist anyway.\n\nFor a `minimal` profile, I'm not sure what the baseline allowlist is. Rather than keep analyzing, I should just tell the user the issue: `tools.allow` expects tool names (like `taskflow` is actually a skill, not a tool), and `minimal` profile combined with `deny: [\"*\"]` is blocking all tools because the allowlist is malformed. The solution is to either remove the deny rule or fix the allowlist to use actual tool names.\n\nWait, the user is saying Feishu doesn't work but webchat does. If I can respond in webchat, maybe the minimal profile restrictions aren't completely blocking everything—perhaps some tools are still accessible through specific pathways. The `session-workspace` tool shows up in traces, which might be why basic webchat functionality is working. Feishu might be failing because it requires tools that are now blocked.\n\nLooking at the actual error from the logs, `gateway connect failed: device identity required` suggests the Feishu channel itself is fine, but there's an authentication issue with the gateway connection. That's why Feishu specifically isn't working while webchat continues to function.\n\nSo the real problem is that `tools.allow` contains skill IDs like \"taskflow\" and \"acp-router\" instead of actual tool names, combined with `deny: [\"*\"]` blocking everything. This is preventing the gateway from properly establishing device identity for Feishu connections.\n\nThe immediate fix is to stop blocking all tools with `deny: [\"*\"]`. I should either remove that restriction entirely or correct the allowlist to use actual tool names rather than skill references. I'm realizing the `alsoAllow` approach might work but could be complex. The real issue is that I don't fully understand what `minimal` profile defaults to, so I should just fix what I know is broken: removing the deny rule and correcting the tool names in the allowlist. But first, let me verify what the actual Feishu error is—I need to look at the full logs to see if there's something specific about feishu communication that's failing.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, I can see the tools.allow warning appearing multiple times starting from 18:55, which aligns with when the gateway restarted after our config changes. So our configuration is definitely causing this. The real problem is that `taskflow` and `acp-router` are skills, not tools—they're in the skills entries but not actual tool names. The system is warning that these entries won't match any tool unless the plugins are enabled, which is exactly what's happening. So the blocking is happening because our allowlist is configured with non-tool identifiers.\n\nThe simplest fix is to remove the deny rule entirely and just use `alsoAllow` to add taskflow and acp-router on top of the minimal profile defaults, rather than trying to override the allowlist directly. minimal` and our `allow` replaces the profile defaults, and nothing matches, so effectively NO tools are allowed.\n\nThe warning \"These entries won't match any tool\" means the allowlist ends up empty after filtering, which with `deny: *` blocks everything.\n\nSo to fix: remove `deny: [\"*\"]` OR change `allow` to actual tool names. Let me just revert the tools section to something sensible.\n\nActually, wait. Let me think about what the user actually wants. They said \"把tools.profile强制改成minimal，同时禁用自动更新、关闭冗余日志\" - they want minimal profile, auto update disabled, and minimal logging. The minimal profile itself should handle tool restrictions. Adding `allow: [\"taskflow\", \"acp-router\"]` and `deny: [\"*\"]` seems to be an extra layer on top.\n\nBut the problem is `taskflow` and `acp-router` aren't tool names. I should check what the minimal profile actually restricts by default. The best approach is to either remove the explicit deny rule entirely, or correct the allowlist to use actual tool names instead of skill identifiers. Let me revert to just the minimal profile setting and see if that works.","thinkingSignature":"ad68b4166e219ab809b9031af97082fd4e484c22978a8bddac9369a88abb75ff"},{"type":"text","text":"找到问题了。日志里有明确的错误：\n\n```\ntools.allow allowlist contains unknown entries (taskflow, acp-router).\nNo callable tools remain after resolving explicit tool allowlist.\n```\n\n`taskflow` 和 `acp-router` 是 **skill 名称**，不是 tool 名称。`tools.allow` 期望的是 tool ID（如 `session-workspace`、`message`），不是你填的 skill 名。而且 `deny: [\"*\"]` 在 allowlist 为空时等于封死所有工具。\n\n这是这次配置改坏掉的，不是飞书本身的问题。需要修复 tools 配置——最简单的方法是去掉 `deny: [\"*\"]`，让 minimal profile 的默认值生效：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jxg0bbjyghw5_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json","edits":[{"oldText":"  \"tools\": {\n    \"profile\": \"minimal\",\n    \"allow\": [\"taskflow\", \"acp-router\"],\n    \"deny\": [\"*\"]\n  },","newText":"  \"tools\": {\n    \"profile\": \"minimal\"\n  },"}]}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":33316,"output":2054,"cacheRead":21148,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":56518,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777806356124,"responseId":"06465f1463f6629a666bfb3af45d6404"}}
