{"type":"message","id":"c1c75225","parentId":"80a34883","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:52:43.543Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the gateway process (PID 91815) is using 70.2% CPU and 568MB of memory. That's very high CPU usage for an idle gateway, which confirms there's something wrong - likely the heavy load from the pdf processing or something similar.\n\nBut more importantly, I notice that clawpanel is running (PID 89386). Maybe clawpanel is what I should be looking at - it might be managing the gateway connection differently.\n\nBut the real issue right now is that the exec tool can run commands, but the openclaw CLI can't connect to the gateway with \"device identity required\". This is a different problem.\n\nLet me think about what \"device identity required\" means in the context of openclaw. \n\nThe gateway config has `auth.mode: \"none\"` and `dangerouslyDisableDeviceAuth: true`, yet it's still demanding device identity. This suggests the WS connection itself needs some form of authentication. Maybe I need to pass a device key or token to authenticate, or perhaps the connection should go through clawpanel instead of directly to the gateway. The `clawpanel-device-key.json` might be the key I need here.\n\nLooking at the config, the gateway is bound to loopback only, which means only local clients can connect. Since clawpanel is running as a local service, it should have access. I could try using openclaw with the --device-id flag to specify the device identity from clawpanel-device-key.json, but I'm not sure if that will work. The real issue seems to be that the connection method or authentication handshake is the problem, not just the device identity itself. Maybe I should try a different approach instead.\n\nActually, I should step back and focus on what the user originally asked. They said messages from Feishu and WeChat have very low success rates and want me to investigate as a common problem. I've confirmed the gateway is running but heavily loaded with high CPU and memory usage. The exec tool commands work fine, but the gateway rejects CLI connections with a \"device identity required\" error. The services themselves seem to be working—the gateway is receiving and routing messages—but the \"device identity required\" error from the gateway is likely what's blocking message delivery. Let me try to get the gateway working first so I can actually test the system, or at least give the user a clear explanation of what's happening.\n\nLet me check if the openclaw CLI has a way to authenticate with device identity, or if I can connect directly using the token from the gateway config.","thinkingSignature":"dd78d5837cce3eaad60a137bc053b717effb2e5bf268008b01055e7293cf975a"},{"type":"text","text":"网关 CPU 占用 70%+，内存 568MB，很不正常。\n\n\"device identity required\" 说明 CLI 无法验证设备身份。让我试试用 token 连接：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_c1lyfzkx38cv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN=\"ffd58c757dc0536a3b5e2192ac5035931f83496bfb9c9327\" openclaw sessions list 2>&1 | head -20","yieldMs":8000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":68534,"output":625,"cacheRead":20974,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90133,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777816344897,"responseId":"06468619e878c52b774981e6e0f6ec2b"}}
