{"type":"message","id":"7313e8d6","parentId":"a8187cf9","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:55:32.773Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_rcxrlu8ihpgg_1","toolName":"gateway","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"gateway\",\n  \"error\": \"gateway closed (1008): device identity required\\nGateway target: ws://127.0.0.1:18789\\nSource: local loopback\\nConfig: /home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json\\nBind: loopback\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"gateway","error":"gateway closed (1008): device identity required\nGateway target: ws://127.0.0.1:18789\nSource: local loopback\nConfig: /home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json\nBind: loopback"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777816532773}}
{"type":"message","id":"abf4c907","parentId":"7313e8d6","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:55:45.913Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still getting \"device identity required\" even with the token. This means the issue is not with authentication - it's something deeper in the WS connection protocol.\n\nLet me think about what \"device identity required\" means in the context of openclaw's WS protocol. Looking at the error:\n- The WS connection closes with code 1008 (Policy Violation)\n- The reason is \"device identity required\"\n\nCode 1008 is \"Protocol Error\" - the server is closing the connection because it received a message that violates the protocol. The \"device identity required\" message is coming from the gateway itself, not from an auth layer.\n\nThis suggests the gateway expects a specific WS message format that includes device identity, and when it doesn't receive it, it closes with 1008.\n\n\nThe gateway probably needs a handshake message with device credentials before it'll accept the connection. And I'm noticing something odd - earlier in this session the gateway tool worked fine, but after some recent restarts it's failing with this error. The current gateway process started at 21:50, which might be relevant to when this broke.\n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully, there's a spike in CPU usage at 21:55 where the event loop nearly froze with a 2020ms delay, which coincides with when the session context ballooned to 67k tokens. That heavy processing might have destabilized something in the gateway. Let me try restarting the gateway and immediately checking if the tool works again, or maybe I should verify the gateway process is even listening on the expected port.","thinkingSignature":"857408f0d7b64ca3ac2736585c7a3a3a18f003f1be6adaf783fbd5496ef83e1c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_v5fsw3uidlbl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ss -tlnp | grep 18789","yieldMs":3000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":76481,"output":356,"cacheRead":20974,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97811,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777816532782,"responseId":"064686d523eacac7d8cdf40394592df0"}}
{"type":"message","id":"edbe65cd","parentId":"abf4c907","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:55:46.841Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_v5fsw3uidlbl_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"LISTEN 0      511        127.0.0.1:18789      0.0.0.0:*    users:((\"node\",pid=91815,fd=25))                                  \nLISTEN 0      511            [::1]:18789         [::]:*    users:((\"node\",pid=91815,fd=26))"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":310,"aggregated":"LISTEN 0      511        127.0.0.1:18789      0.0.0.0:*    users:((\"node\",pid=91815,fd=25))                                  \nLISTEN 0      511            [::1]:18789         [::]:*    users:((\"node\",pid=91815,fd=26))","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777816546841}}
{"type":"message","id":"32856023","parentId":"edbe65cd","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:56:00.655Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Gateway is listening on port 18789. The issue is with the WS protocol. Let me try to understand the openclaw WS protocol. \n\nLooking at the error, the gateway is closing WS connections with code 1008 and reason \"device identity required\". This sounds like the gateway's transport layer is rejecting connections that don't present valid credentials.\n\nWait - I think I understand. The openclaw CLI and the openclaw gateway communicate over a WS protocol that includes a handshake. The \"device identity\" might refer to a device key that the CLI needs to present.\n\nBut `openclaw sessions` works! This is very confusing. How can `openclaw sessions` work but `gateway config.get` fail?\n \nThe difference might be that `openclaw sessions` reads directly from the session file, while `gateway config.get` actually opens a WS connection to the gateway. So maybe the WS connection itself is where the device identity check happens, and that's what's failing.\n\nLooking at the `openclaw gateway status` output showing \"Capability: admin-capable\", it seems like the gateway should accept admin connections. But I'm also noticing something important about the clawpanel device key - that's what identifies the control UI to the gateway. Maybe the issue is that the gateway is only accepting connections from registered devices, and the `openclaw` CLI tool I'm using isn't registered as a valid device. Let me think about whether there's a way to authenticate with the gateway first before making admin calls.","thinkingSignature":"ce4e1b34d7595b015ac1216c2bba848c9755f3efba1a00cc85e21ec2f2a0afba"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_06ewlm71ukls_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw help 2>&1 | head -40","yieldMs":5000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":76933,"output":344,"cacheRead":20974,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":98251,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777816546852,"responseId":"064686e342752c0ba054d2c029027584"}}
{"type":"message","id":"bf6b64f2","parentId":"32856023","timestamp":"2026-05-03T13:56:01.702Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_06ewlm71ukls_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"🦞 OpenClaw 2026.5.2 (8b2a6e5) — Runs on a Raspberry Pi. Dreams of a rack in Iceland.\n\nUsage: openclaw [options] [command]\n\nOptions:\n  --container <name>   Run the CLI inside a running Podman/Docker container\n                       named <name> (default: env OPENCLAW_CONTAINER)\n  --dev                Dev profile: isolate state under ~/.openclaw-dev, default\n                       gateway port 19001, and shift derived ports\n                       (browser/canvas)\n  -h, --help           Display help for command\n  --log-level <level>  Global log level override for file + console\n                       (silent|fatal|error|warn|info|debug|trace)\n  --no-color           Disable ANSI colors\n  --profile <name>     Use a named profile (isolates\n                       OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR/OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH under\n                       ~/.openclaw-<name>)\n  -V, --version        output the version number\n\nCommands:\n  Hint: commands suffixed with * have subcommands. Run <command> --help for details.\n  acp *                Agent Control Protocol tools\n  agent                Run one agent turn via the Gateway\n  agents *             Manage isolated agents (workspaces, auth, routing)\n  approvals *          Manage exec approvals (gateway or node host)\n  backup *             Create and verify local backup archives for OpenClaw\n                       state\n  capability *         Run provider-backed inference commands (fallback alias:\n                       infer)\n  channels *           Manage connected chat channels (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\n  chat                 Open a local terminal UI (alias for tui --local)\n  clawbot *            Legacy clawbot command aliases\n  commitments *        List and manage inferred follow-up commitments\n  completion           Generate shell completion script\n  config *             Non-interactive config helpers\n                       (get/set/unset/file/validate). Default: starts guided\n                       setup.\n  configure            Interactive configuration for credentials, channels,\n                       gateway, and agent defaults"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":457,"aggregated":"🦞 OpenClaw 2026.5.2 (8b2a6e5) — Runs on a Raspberry Pi. Dreams of a rack in Iceland.\n\nUsage: openclaw [options] [command]\n\nOptions:\n  --container <name>   Run the CLI inside a running Podman/Docker container\n                       named <name> (default: env OPENCLAW_CONTAINER)\n  --dev                Dev profile: isolate state under ~/.openclaw-dev, default\n                       gateway port 19001, and shift derived ports\n                       (browser/canvas)\n  -h, --help           Display help for command\n  --log-level <level>  Global log level override for file + console\n                       (silent|fatal|error|warn|info|debug|trace)\n  --no-color           Disable ANSI colors\n  --profile <name>     Use a named profile (isolates\n                       OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR/OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH under\n                       ~/.openclaw-<name>)\n  -V, --version        output the version number\n\nCommands:\n  Hint: commands suffixed with * have subcommands. Run <command> --help for details.\n  acp *                Agent Control Protocol tools\n  agent                Run one agent turn via the Gateway\n  agents *             Manage isolated agents (workspaces, auth, routing)\n  approvals *          Manage exec approvals (gateway or node host)\n  backup *             Create and verify local backup archives for OpenClaw\n                       state\n  capability *         Run provider-backed inference commands (fallback alias:\n                       infer)\n  channels *           Manage connected chat channels (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\n  chat                 Open a local terminal UI (alias for tui --local)\n  clawbot *            Legacy clawbot command aliases\n  commitments *        List and manage inferred follow-up commitments\n  completion           Generate shell completion script\n  config *             Non-interactive config helpers\n                       (get/set/unset/file/validate). Default: starts guided\n                       setup.\n  configure            Interactive configuration for credentials, channels,\n                       gateway, and agent defaults","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777816561701}}
